From Mark Kilpela Subject Re A question about outlet In article Russ Crisp wrote Hello I'm considering modernizing some old wiring in my home and I need a little advice on outlet Several outlets are the old 'two prong' type without the Naturally the wire feeding these outlets is WITHOUT the ground I noticed at the fusebox that some circuits have the with ground and that on these circuits the ground wire was tied to the same bus as the neutral white Here's my It seems to me that I'd have the same electrical circuit if I hooked the neutral D D D D D D D D D D Da jumper from the neutral over to the ground screw on new 'three prong' grounding What's wrong with my reasoning here First it will not pass a National Electrical code Secondly The neutral wire is current carrying and the ground wire shouldn't be or only during a fault The reason the neutral and ground are tied together in the panel is the tranformer on the power pole has a grounded center tap secondary with the grounded center tap the This gives to neutral ground from each side of the transformer and across the So in effect the neutral and ground should be at the same Mark Kilpela email Michigan Technological University School of Technology